<doc id="192266" wikidata="Q977297" url="?curid=192266" title="Trace class">
<text>In mathematics, specifically functional analysis, a trace-class operator is a linear operator for which a trace may be defined, such that the trace is a finite number independent of the choice of basis used to compute the trace. This trace of trace-class operators generalizes the trace of matrices studied in linear algebra. All trace-class operators are compact operators. 

In quantum mechanics, quantum states are described by density matrices, which are certain trace class operators. 

Trace-class operators are essentially the same as nuclear operators, though many authors reserve the term &quot;trace-class operator&quot; for the special case of nuclear operators on Hilbert spaces and use the term &quot;nuclear operator&quot; in more general topological vector spaces (such as Banach spaces).

Note that the trace operator studied in partial differential equations is an unrelated concept.

== Definition ==
Let formula_1 be a separable Hilbert space, formula_2 an orthonormal basis and formula_3 a positive bounded linear operator on formula_1. The trace of formula_5 is denoted by formula_6 and defined as
:formula_7
independent of the choice of orthonormal basis. A (not necessarily positive) bounded linear operator formula_8 is called trace class &quot;if and only if&quot;
:formula_9
where formula_10 denotes the positive-semidefinite Hermitian square root.

The trace-norm of a trace class operator is defined as
formula_11
One can show that the trace-norm is a norm on the space of all trace class operators formula_12 and that formula_12, with the trace-norm, becomes a Banach space.

When formula_1 is finite-dimensional, every (positive) operator is trace class. For formula_5 this definition coincides with that of the trace of a matrix. If formula_1 is complex, then formula_5 is always self-adjoint (i.e. formula_18) though the converse is not necessarily true.

== Equivalent formulations ==
Given a bounded linear operator formula_19, each of the following statements is equivalent to formula_20 being in the trace class:
* formula_21 is finite for every orthonormal basis formula_22 of .
* is a nuclear operator
