<doc id="192294" wikidata="Q4530507" url="?curid=192294" title="Screened Poisson equation">
<text>In physics, the screened Poisson equation is a Poisson equation, which arises in (for example) the Klein–Gordon equation, electric field screening in plasmas, and nonlocal granular fluidity in granular flow.

==Statement of the equation==

The equation is
formula_1

where formula_2 is the Laplace operator, &quot;λ&quot; is a constant that expresses the &quot;screening&quot;, &quot;f&quot; is an arbitrary function of position (known as the &quot;source function&quot;) and &quot;u&quot; is the function to be determined.

In the homogeneous case (&quot;f&quot;=0), the screened Poisson equation is the same as the time-independent Klein–Gordon equation. In the inhomogeneous case, the screened Poisson equation is very similar to the inhomogeneous Helmholtz equation, the only difference being the sign within the brackets.

=== Electrostatics ===
In electric-field screening, screened Poisson equation for the electric potential formula_3 is usually written as (SI units)

formula_4

where formula_5 is the screening length, formula_6 is the charge density produced by an external field in the absence of screening and formula_7 is the vacuum permittivity. This equation can be derived in several screening models like Thomas–Fermi screening in solid-state physics and Debye screening in plasmas.

==Solutions==

===Three dimensions===

Without loss of generality, we will take &quot;λ&quot; to be non-negative. When &quot;λ&quot; is zero, the equation reduces to Poisson&#x27;s equation. Therefore, when &quot;λ&quot; is very small, the solution approaches that of the unscreened Poisson equation, which, in dimension formula_8, is a superposition of 1/&quot;r&quot; functions weighted by the source function &quot;f&quot;:

formula_9

On the other hand, when &quot;λ&quot; is extremely large, &quot;u&quot; approaches the value &quot;f&quot;/&quot;λ&quot;2, which goes to zero as &quot;λ&quot; goes to infinity. As we shall see, the solution for intermediate values of &quot;λ&quot; behaves as a superposition of screened (or damped) 1/&quot;r&quot; functions, with &quot;λ&quot; behaving as the strength of the screening.

The screened Poisson equation can be solved for general &quot;f&quot; using the method of Green&#x27;s functions. The Green&#x27;s function &quot;G&quot; is defined by

formula_10
where δ3 is a delta function with unit mass concentrated at the origin of R3.

Assuming &quot;u&quot; and its derivatives vanish at large &quot;r&quot;, we may perform a continuous Fourier transform in spatial coordinates:

formula_11

where the integral is taken over all space. It is then straightforward to show that

formula_12

The Green&#x27;s function in &quot;r&quot; is therefore given by the inverse Fourier transform,

formula_13

This integral may be evaluated using spherical coordinates in &quot;k&quot;-space. The integration over the angular coordinates is straightforward, and the integral reduces to one over the radial wavenumber formula_14:

formula_15

This may be evaluated using contour integration. The result is:

formula_16

The solution to the full problem is then given by

formula_17

As stated above, this is a superposition of screened 1/&quot;r&quot; functions, weighted by the source function &quot;f&quot; and with &quot;λ&quot; acting as the strength of the screening. The screened 1/&quot;r&quot; function is often encountered in physics as a screened Coulomb potential, also called a &quot;Yukawa potential&quot;.

===Two dimensions===
In two dimensions:
In the case of a magnetized plasma, the screened Poisson equation is quasi-2D:
formula_18
with formula_19 and formula_20, with formula_21 the magnetic field and formula_22 is the (ion) Larmor radius.
The two-dimensional Fourier Transform of the associated Green&#x27;s function is:
formula_23
The 2D screened Poisson equation yields:
formula_24
The Green&#x27;s function is therefore given by the inverse Fourier transform:
formula_25
This integral can be calculated using polar coordinates in k-space:
formula_26
The integration over the angular coordinate gives a Bessel function, and the integral reduces to one over the radial wavenumber formula_14:
formula_28

==Connection to the Laplace distribution==
The Green&#x27;s functions in both 2D and 3D are identical to the probability density function of the multivariate Laplace distribution for two and three dimensions respectively.

==Application in differential geometry==
The homogeneous case, studied in the context of differential geometry, involving Einstein warped product manifolds, explores cases where the warped function satisfies the homogeneous version of the screened Poisson equation. Under specific conditions, the manifold size, Ricci curvature, and screening parameter are interconnected via a quadratic relationship.

==See also==
* Yukawa interaction

